Media notes: Peregrine Falcon | www.haussparrow.com
Observation Details: Observed from kayak south of the boardwalk platform, across inlet, perched in a small tree growing just off shore (South Marsh). It's attention was primarily focused on overhead flying Tree Swallows. It also left this perch and did a short flight over the marshes and returning to the same perch after about 30 seconds. Eventually it flew off South along the river. There were no bands on any of the legs.

Vocalized several times, in the Bay Area where they usually are. Adult was later seen perched on one of its favorite perches.   Spent about an hour with the bird. at one point they got scared off from its perch because a dog came by and then it went to the nest that they've used in years past and started making a squeaky call, normal screechy call they do.  After 5 to 10 minutes of the bird on the nest making its squeaky call, a second falcon showed up looking similar to the female that was here last year (less dark wings & body and more off color chest than the pure White of adult number one). When bird 2 showed up that flew around a bit and then flew off and bird number one followed her.   Bird number one returned 2 minutes later, and perched near the nest, staying silent. No idea where bird number 2 went.   Bird number one eventually took off towards the mainland.

Observed five Peregrine Falcon, one female, one male, and three fledglings. The adults were on wings most of the tome hunting for small birds of which they caught one Least Sandpiper and one young Snowy Egret. The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

Observation Details: Surprised and delighted to see a Peregrine Falcon hunting in central Frankston. First seen after hearing some very strident Noisy Minor alarm calls. It eventually took flight again and did a number of low hunting circuits over and around garden. It then moved on.

Observation Details: Found the original one that was very vocal with the only description that comes to mind was that it sounds like short yips or yipping or short shrieking barks. When this one came down lower and went to perch. I had to find it! And when I did. There was a second Peregrine Falcon. I slowly walked with camera in hand long ways next to my leg and didn't' look directly at them. short peripherals to make sure they were still there. I sat down and started taking photos of the best looking one with the better setting for a photo. Twenty minutes had gone by and both started yipping and looking up. Managed to catch two more streaming and right into direction of the sun. Then a third straggler streamed above. My 2 blandair birds were getting ready to take off. And when they did they elevated very rapidly and had caught the same stream and were gone. The Peregrine Falcon is my all time favorite bird!

First observed diving at American Wigeon at around 10:20. It perched for about 30 minutes in a tree hanging over the west side of the lake near the AmWi. It flew toward the dam and perched for a brief time on a log at the lake shore and then repositioned to a tree near the entrance building and pier near the dam. Flew over the dam and scattered the ring billed gulls before swooping back up the lake. After I lost sight of it, Joe reported it ate the American Wigeon about 10 minutes later. Checkerboard breast (some breast feathers tawny) and underside of wings, strong mustache stripe, pale eyebrow, brown streak along crown, tawny throat, dark blue back, yellow legs, primaries did not extend beyond tail. Banded on May 21st 2021 in New Jersey with Band Number 1947-31935 BM71 Black over Green by the State of New Jersey - Nongame, Kathleen Clark. The Peregrine Falcon was too young to fly when banded on 21 May 2021. Since Peregrine Falcons fledge around 40 days, this individual must be about 7-8 months old.

Observation Details: As I looked around the inlet I spotted this Juvenile Peregrine Falcon feeding on something. I tried to figure out what it was by taking photos and looking for the remnants of the meal but couldn't tell exactly. It was a peep species but I don't know which one. I kept a good distance away so it would be undisturbed while eating. I never approached it directly and wanted to make it feel comfortable with me being there. After it was done it flew to different spots and twice landed within 50 feet of where I was standing. I was not seen as a threat. Part of that is likely this juveniles innocence to the ways of people and part of that was the respect I showed it. I thought how great it would be if all wildlife could be comfortable around people. I spent probably 20-30 minutes just getting lost in the moment. I felt like it was just me and the falcon on the beach. Maybe it felt the same.

Observation Details: Cuando llego Urraca está en la antena y Brisa dando vueltas al edificio reclamando y portando una paloma. Al momento se posa con la presa en la azotea, y la joven baja a recogerla. Brisa se va pero vuelve al instante y se posa junto a la caja. 10:57. Madrigal aparece volando desde el sureste, zona puente de los Tres Árboles, remontando mientras reclama. Tras un minuto aproximadamente, se va por donde ha venido. 11:01. Urraca vuelve a la antena. 11:09. Baja a donde está su madre y hacen intercambio de posadero. 11:12. Llega Madrigal y se posa no visible. 12:03. Llega Viento y se posa en una viga. 12:13. Brisa vuela dirección este. 12:29. Viento reclama amenazante ante el paso de una calzada (f.c.) pero no se mueve de su posadero. 12:51. Pasa una calzada (f.o.) a una distancia aproximada a la de la anterior y Viento no se inmuta. 12:55. Viento reclama de alerta pero no consigo ver la amenaza. 13:02. Urraca se asoma a la cornisa, junto a su padre. Reclaman ambos. 13:07. Urraca y Madrigal vuelan varios minutos alrededor del edificio, jugando entre ellas. 13:12. Se posan en zona no visible. 13:16. Un milano negro baja a la azotea, seguramente a por restos de presas. Viento arremete con furia sobre él y lo expulsa. Una de las jóvenes también azuza al milano pero manteniendo la distancia. Viento realiza picados terribles sobre la rapaz que no tarda en huir. Cuando me voy están las dos jóvenes en la azotea. Una en la antena y la otra no visible. ¡No ha pasado ni una paloma bravía en toda la mañana!

Seen at 9:20 when the 100+ ducks, 50+ coots, assorted shorebirds & gulls sounded a terrible clamorous alarm. The ducks & coots went into the water, the coots into a huddle and the ducks into a long line several ducks deep. After scanning the sky in vain, I saw a Peregrine Falcon sitting a few yards further up the beach, eating a coot. Gradually the ducks & coots started to go back to shore, then at 9:30 a runner went past the falcon, which flushed and circled over the water. The alarm resumed, and the falcon landed in a nearby palm tree. Eventually I walked on, leaving the falcon in the tree. About 10 minutes later I looked back and saw the falcon had returned to eating the coot on the beach.

Media notes: Advanced subadult (near-adult)
Observation Details: Right as we were launching and heading towards Avocet Pt, we saw that all the Ring-billed Gulls, etc suddenly flush off the tip of Avocet Pt and suspected there was a predator in the area. Sure enough, sitting on a log along the south end of Avocet was a Peregrine. The falcon flew to Green Island as we approached, and was seen again later in the morning briefly harassing the Killdeer on Avocet Pt. No leg bands. Thought to be a full adult in the field, photos show that this is actually a very advanced subadult...showing retained juveniles feathers in some areas (outer secondaries, upperwing coverts, underwing coverts, uppertail coverts, upper breast, and leg feathers).

Observation Details: Absolutely incredible watching the strength and aggression of these impressive birds. I saw the adult male perched screaming on the top of a fir when all of a sudden it dove down and almost killed a great horned owl! The owl flew into a red willow and the falcon proceeding to continue shrieking at it for hours. Eventually the owl attempted to make a break for it but was struck down by the ferocious killer... Later on the hike I observed the falcons mating which completely surprised me, I did some research and came up empty handed as to why they would mate outside of the breeding season.

Media notes: falcon flushed a huge flock of gulls and managed to get a slow Heerman’s Gull
Observation Details: Peregrine flushed a huge flock of gulls and managed to catch one slow Heermann’s Gull; Keith Gress got me some info on this bird’s age and sex from expert at GGRO. Based on molt, he aged her at 2-3 years old. The brown feathers are adult feathers. In the female they have juvenile plumage, then the brown, then the gray. “The buffy and unbarred breast is more typical of continental birds, but with all of the cross-polination on this species, it’s possible we have that here now too.”

Media notes: On a Lesser Flamingo kill

Observation Details: Over the course of the first 1.5 hrs after sunrise, these two miscreants (both youngsters) spent almost the entire period chasing back-tracking passerines as they struggled back to landfall having overshot at dawn. Clear skies, cool temps, and a NE wind made for excellent overnight migrating conditions, but as happens in such conditions every fall there were at least 25 passerines (mostly Myrtles) that I watched struggle back to Pipit and the Toplands beach. The Peregrines were able to snatch the occasional songbird and then using the lift from the strong E wind remained aloft way out over the open lake and ate the catch on the wing. An easy breakfast snack for these two young PEFAs.

Locality: Edwin B. Forsythe NWR--Wildlife Drive (8-mile auto tour loop only)
Observation Details: Immature (probable) 'North American' type by overall darker plumage, darker crown (although an individual with some paler mottling), thick sideburns. This bird was insanely approachable; perched along the road on a guard rail. It’s not every day that you hear the words ‘friendly’ and ‘Peregrine’ in the same sentence. Refuge staff have said that it isn’t one of the locally-hatched birds as it doesn’t have the proper leg bands. Having worked with Peregrines this past summer in Virginia, I can say that the immature birds are pretty hard to get close to once they are able to fly. I think it is exceptionally rare to have the opportunity to observe and photograph an immature bird at this distance. The weather was pretty gloomy when my friends and I stopped by the refuge on January 2nd, but the Peregrine was right where other birders had reported it and I was happy to snap off a few shots while we slowly toured the auto loop.  The other Peregrine was perched on the nesting tower.

As I looked around the inlet I spotted this Juvenile Peregrine Falcon feeding on something. I tried to figure out what it was by taking photos and looking for the remnants of the meal but couldn't tell exactly. It was a peep species but I don't know which one. I kept a good distance away so it would be undisturbed while eating. I never approached it directly and wanted to make it feel comfortable with me being there. After it was done it flew to different spots and twice landed within 50 feet of where I was standing. I was not seen as a threat. Part of that is likely this juveniles innocence to the ways of people and part of that was the respect I showed it. I thought how great it would be if all wildlife could be comfortable around people. I spent probably 20-30 minutes just getting lost in the moment. I felt like it was just me and the falcon on the beach. Maybe it felt the same.

Media notes: It was not vocalizing, but seemed to be throwing up bits of coot. It did this several times.
Observation Details: Seen at 9:20 when the 100+ ducks, 50+ coots, assorted shorebirds & gulls sounded a terrible clamorous alarm. The ducks & coots went into the water, the coots into a huddle and the ducks into a long line several ducks deep. After scanning the sky in vain, I saw a Peregrine Falcon sitting a few yards further up the beach, eating a coot. Gradually the ducks & coots started to go back to shore, then at 9:30 a runner went past the falcon, which flushed and circled over the water. The alarm resumed, and the falcon landed in a nearby palm tree. Eventually I walked on, leaving the falcon in the tree. About 10 minutes later I looked back and saw the falcon had returned to eating the coot on the beach.

Observed five Peregrine Falcon, one female, one male, and three fledglings. The adults were on wings most of the tome hunting for small birds of which they caught one Least Sandpiper and one young Snowy Egret. The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

Observation Details: Migratory Tundra type of subspecies calidus/japonicus. Adult. We note that it is difficult to separate migratory Peregrines in Australia to subspecies and that eBird does not recognise japonicus as a separate taxon. A dark peregrine with white cheek patch and broad moustachial stripe. It is interesting to note that the shape of the moustachial stripe can vary depending on angle and if the bird is flying vs perched for example: https://ebird.org/checklist/S50611590  This is not the same individual as that seen and photographed at Buffalo Creek on 23 Dec 2022 (https://ebird.org/checklist/S124455395) and 28 Dec 2022 (https://ebird.org/checklist/S124954753). Photos indicate that bird was a juvenile.

Very exciting to see these birds activity hunting! The male is E39 (Perry) and the female is C94 (Rosalee). Here's the Chicago Peregrine Program information on her: Winter Wanderings-- Not all adult Peregrines stay near their breeding sites to winter. A few females seem to "pair up" with a wintering solo male and then return to their breeding site the next spring. We saw this in the winter wanderings of Rockford's Louise. Here it is again with a Chicago/Bensenville sighting of a falcon named Rosalee. Rosalee fledged from a site in Madison and breeds up in Rothschild WI. During winters she has periodically been caught on webcams and sighted by photographer/birders. Just this fall she had traveled from Rothschild, to Jefferson WI to Milwaukee and then to Chicago/Bensenville at the same location she was in Jan 2019. It may be that Chicago is her winter home and webcams just caught her making her way down south. And being a peregrine attracted to Peregrines, she was photographed with a male at each site.  (Before you make something into THAT - it is likely something as simple as finding a good hunting ground by following a resident falcon).

These data were gathered as part of the Florida Keys Hawkwatch (FKH) migration monitoring project by official FKH 2015 counters (vetted and experienced migration monitoring field technicians: Rafael Galvez and Ted Keyel). For more information about project history, protocols and methods visit the projects official website: floridakeyshawkwatch.wordpress.com. For a complete yearly report, email taspublisher@gmail.com. All avian species as part of this project are monitored from two sites in the Middle Keys. At Long Key State Park, by morning flight surveys and transect counts each morning from September 1 through the mid-November, during which all detections are documented by distance, habitat use, behavior and number of individuals using standardized protocols. All avian species are monitored from Curry Hammock State Park (CHSP) during that same time period, in a daily sequence of 7 to 8 point counts, using methods standardized for the site and in use since 1996. Counts take place from 09:00 to 16:00 DST, and all bird detections are documented for species and number of individuals. Raptors are additionally documented to include age, sex and any other plumage or morphological details for each individual when detectable, in addition to flight direction, lateral distance, flight height and flight path; only southbound totals for the entire duration of the daily count per site are included here (CHSP minimum 7 hours each day). Every hour, wind direction and speed, temperature, sky conditions, flight details and observer information is logged into standardized forms. Data are carefully entered into eBird after being scrutinized and reviewed on paper data forms by the official technicians only.

I quickly grabbed my camera and was able to get several unobstructed images before a much smaller bird harassed it and it flew off, eventually flying across the road to alight on a similar tower several hundred yards away.  Will add image later.

Immature. Just before we were about to leave a first time, we saw a large mixed group of waterfowl suddenly fly towards mid-lake. Eventually, this bird appeared in hot pursuit. We were then treated to it grabbing a female lesser scaup out of the air.  It flew her back to shore, where she then dragged them both into the water deep enough that the peregrine was forced to let go. Superb drama! We then got great photos of this bird on a close perch after a bit more, less dramatic, hunting.

Observation Details: Peregrine flushed a huge flock of gulls and managed to catch one slow Heermann’s Gull; Keith Gress got me some info on this bird’s age and sex from expert at GGRO. Based on molt, he aged her at 2-3 years old. The brown feathers are adult feathers. In the female they have juvenile plumage, then the brown, then the gray. “The buffy and unbarred breast is more typical of continental birds, but with all of the cross-polination on this species, it’s possible we have that here now too.”

Observed five Peregrine Falcon, one female, one male, and three fledglings. The adults were on wings most of the tome hunting for small birds of which they caught one Least Sandpiper and one young Snowy Egret. The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

As I looked around the inlet I spotted this Juvenile Peregrine Falcon feeding on something. I tried to figure out what it was by taking photos and looking for the remnants of the meal but couldn't tell exactly. It was a peep species but I don't know which one. I kept a good distance away so it would be undisturbed while eating. I never approached it directly and wanted to make it feel comfortable with me being there. After it was done it flew to different spots and twice landed within 50 feet of where I was standing. I was not seen as a threat. Part of that is likely this juveniles innocence to the ways of people and part of that was the respect I showed it. I thought how great it would be if all wildlife could be comfortable around people. I spent probably 20-30 minutes just getting lost in the moment. I felt like it was just me and the falcon on the beach. Maybe it felt the same.

Media notes: Thin malar, pale forehead, pronounced supercilium, and wide pale auriculars- contacting orbital feathers. Slight horizontal break in malar just below eye.
Observation Details: *Rare; juvenile perched on the breakwater. Separated from the expected F. p. anatum subspecies in part by extensively pale forehead, auriculars and supercilium, leaving a very narrow malar stripe. Upperwing coverts showing wide buffy margins as well, pointing to the arctic-breeding F. p. tundrius. Confirmed by Erik Bruhnke. Photos

Media notes: Saw one individual (mostly female) calling from a rock on a cliff, it kept returning to the same spot and there was some base it looked like a nest but there were no eggs or chicks in it. The other individual (mostly male) kept circling around the peak and then came back and never sat to the individual sitting on the nest probably a mating ritual. After a while the other one took off and both started vocalising and then started doing some mid air acrobatics where they fly together and suddenly one individual drive bombs the other (probably the display).

Cuando llego Urraca está en la antena y Brisa dando vueltas al edificio reclamando y portando una paloma. Al momento se posa con la presa en la azotea, y la joven baja a recogerla. Brisa se va pero vuelve al instante y se posa junto a la caja. 10:57. Madrigal aparece volando desde el sureste, zona puente de los Tres Árboles, remontando mientras reclama. Tras un minuto aproximadamente, se va por donde ha venido. 11:01. Urraca vuelve a la antena. 11:09. Baja a donde está su madre y hacen intercambio de posadero. 11:12. Llega Madrigal y se posa no visible. 12:03. Llega Viento y se posa en una viga. 12:13. Brisa vuela dirección este. 12:29. Viento reclama amenazante ante el paso de una calzada (f.c.) pero no se mueve de su posadero. 12:51. Pasa una calzada (f.o.) a una distancia aproximada a la de la anterior y Viento no se inmuta. 12:55. Viento reclama de alerta pero no consigo ver la amenaza. 13:02. Urraca se asoma a la cornisa, junto a su padre. Reclaman ambos. 13:07. Urraca y Madrigal vuelan varios minutos alrededor del edificio, jugando entre ellas. 13:12. Se posan en zona no visible. 13:16. Un milano negro baja a la azotea, seguramente a por restos de presas. Viento arremete con furia sobre él y lo expulsa. Una de las jóvenes también azuza al milano pero manteniendo la distancia. Viento realiza picados terribles sobre la rapaz que no tarda en huir. Cuando me voy están las dos jóvenes en la azotea. Una en la antena y la otra no visible. ¡No ha pasado ni una paloma bravía en toda la mañana!

Observed five Peregrine Falcon, one female, one male, and three fledglings. The adults were on wings most of the tome hunting for small birds of which they caught one Least Sandpiper and one young Snowy Egret. The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

Very cool.

Juvenile with pale forehead and midcrown, pale supercilium, narrow dark malar stripe. Malar stripe not as narrow as on Prairie Falcon. Yellow feet and orbital ring, pale yellow cere.  Thin malar stripe and strong supercilium made it similar enough to juvenile Prairie Falcon to give us pause.  But no black axillaries in flight, and white cheek doesn't extend up behind eye like in Prairie.  Similar to Plate 569 in Wheeler's Raptors of Western N. America, which shows Tundrius ssp.  Photos.

Cuando llego están Brisa y Urraca en dos vigas de la esquina noreste. Ambas han comido. 09:39. Brisa vuela después de que la joven la acosara pedigüeña. 9:44. Urraca se lanza a por una paloma torcaz, sin éxito. Ambas se posan en la cara sur. 10:31. Gritos de alerta de Brisa ante el paso alto de una calzada (f.c.). 10:51. Gritos de alerta por el paso de un buitre negro. Cuando me voy se quedan ambas en la cara sur.

Cuando llego está Brisa en la antena. 10:04. Arremete contra una paloma torcaz, sin éxito, y se posa en la cara sur. 10:30. Brisa cacarea y sale a marcar el paso de un buitre negro. En este momento, asoma uno de los pollos y se queda en la entrada. Es Urraca. 10:39. Vuelve Brisa a posarse donde estaba. 11:24. Sale un segundo pollo y se posa bajo la antena y junto a la chimenea. El primero no está visible. Confirmo que es Madrigal al leer la anilla. 11:50. Brisa se va. 12:16. Vuelve y se posa en la antena. Los pollos no son visibles ahora pero están fuera. 12:29. Llega Viento, se posa un momento, y se marcha enseguida. Cuando me voy solo es visible Brisa.

Locality: Great River Road, Godfrey, Illinois, US (38.911, -90.22)
Observation Details: At nest site

This is a active nest . You can see the four chicks from the viewing point. (as pictures show, three are in a good view but just the wing shows of the forth one) The adults are nearby protecting the chicks.

Observed five Peregrine Falcon, one female, one male, and three fledglings. The adults were on wings most of the tome hunting for small birds of which they caught one Least Sandpiper and one young Snowy Egret. The adults were observed to also attack and chase away several Brown Pelicans as well as a few transfers from the of small birds captured by the male to the female which were brought to the nest by her for the three fledglings. The three fledglings were observed  flapping their wings while in the nest on the cliff and coming to the edge to view out. A band on the right leg was visible with the number 16 above and letters AC below. Those were the only number/letter combination visible in my photos Very active day.

As I looked around the inlet I spotted this Juvenile Peregrine Falcon feeding on something. I tried to figure out what it was by taking photos and looking for the remnants of the meal but couldn't tell exactly. It was a peep species but I don't know which one. I kept a good distance away so it would be undisturbed while eating. I never approached it directly and wanted to make it feel comfortable with me being there. After it was done it flew to different spots and twice landed within 50 feet of where I was standing. I was not seen as a threat. Part of that is likely this juveniles innocence to the ways of people and part of that was the respect I showed it. I thought how great it would be if all wildlife could be comfortable around people. I spent probably 20-30 minutes just getting lost in the moment. I felt like it was just me and the falcon on the beach. Maybe it felt the same.

Locality: Edwin B. Forsythe NWR--Wildlife Drive (8-mile auto tour loop only)
Observation Details: Immature (probable) 'North American' type by overall darker plumage, darker crown (although an individual with some paler mottling), thick sideburns. This bird was insanely approachable; perched along the road on a guard rail. It’s not every day that you hear the words ‘friendly’ and ‘Peregrine’ in the same sentence. Refuge staff have said that it isn’t one of the locally-hatched birds as it doesn’t have the proper leg bands. Having worked with Peregrines this past summer in Virginia, I can say that the immature birds are pretty hard to get close to once they are able to fly. I think it is exceptionally rare to have the opportunity to observe and photograph an immature bird at this distance. The weather was pretty gloomy when my friends and I stopped by the refuge on January 2nd, but the Peregrine was right where other birders had reported it and I was happy to snap off a few shots while we slowly toured the auto loop.  The other Peregrine was perched on the nesting tower.

Great looks at this bird (there may have been a second one) as it swooped from fairly high up and almost out of sight, then came roaring down along the edge of the pond to flush the shorebirds. At one point it came within less than 20 metres of me as I was standing on the berm. It was hard to keep the bird in focus with the 7D2 and 500mm lens (equivalent of 16X) as it was constantly moving so quickly. It was often partially back lit, so the photos needed more processing to be satisfactory.

Media notes: With American Coot

Observation Details: we watched in awe the hunting speed of a large, very dark, immature female Peregrine as it jetted low after shorebird and gull flocks. It later landed in the tallest tree next to the Center, and was evident how dark - above and below - this bird was. It's large blackish "helmet" was also very wide, unlike the thinner "sideburns" typical of the tundra race. It sure looked like a juvenile Pacific (Peale's) race.  Photos were obtained by Frank, Lesley, and Malcolm - which will be studied and consulted with raptor experts.  While watching this perched bird, another PF was seen chasing a bird out over the last cottage.

Observation Details: Possible/probable Tundra (tundrius) Peregrine - very cool-looking bird. Very high up and moving south quickly at 5:45pm. From afar, I initially got excited about it being a possible Prairie Falcon due to it being very light below and having a very notably thin ‘mustache’ (opposed to the thick broad mask more typical of our resident Peregrines). As it got closer, however, there were no dark axillaries on it and the mustache was too thick for PRFA - it was a Peregrine but looked pretty unique. I took distant photos and one digiscope video as well, but the bird was soon gone to the south. I am still doing some more research into Tundra Peregrine Falcons but I think this bird is a great contender. Photos show that it had some blood on its chest.

A Peregrine Falcon sitting on the 3 foot wide metal ledge of our office building, 15 stories high. We often saw this bird and other Peregrines when they would bring pigeons to eat that they had just caught in downtown Minneapolis.. Today this bird did not have a pigeon. We would also see these Peregrines flying their usual "route" through the tall canyons of the skyscrapers as they hunted for pigeons.

The East Rock Peregrine Falcons during the 2023 breeding season.  Summary:  Two fledglings are on the south perch ledge. Fledgling #1 remains sitting on the Redcedar at the edge of the ledge (15 minutes). Fledgling #2 is upslope on the rocky ledge. The adult female continues on the outer portion of the scrape ledge as she holds a woodpecker kill in her talons. She will remain here with prey for at least 36 minutes. At 1:54 P.M., fledgling #1 leaves the Redcedar perch and returns to the south perch ledge, where it performs a left leg and wing stretch. It then walks further upslope. At 2:09:30 P.M., the adult male (tiercel) lands on the south perch ledge with a small prey item. Fledgling #1 lunges at the tiercel with raised wings and open beak. Fledgling #2 flies down and joins the exchange. Fledgling #1 seizes the prey item, cradles it with open wings, and turns away from the tiercel, moving upslope. Fledgling #2 approaches more closely, beak open. The tiercel lifts off the ledge at 2:09:34, having stayed a total of four seconds. Fledgling #1 turns and moves to the edge of the ledge, then walks to the far side of the ledge with prey in mouth. Fledgling #2 watches. The adult female (peregrine) remains on the scrape ledge with woodpecker prey, where she has been observing the tiercel and the two fledglings on the south perch ledge. Now, she begins to preen.  #1 2:09:30 P.M. - the adult male (tiercel) flies to the south perch ledge with small prey item. #2 2:09:30 P.M. - fledgling #1 approaches the tiercel. #3 2:09:31 P.M. - fledgling goes after the prey item. #4 2:09:31 P.M. - fledgling #1 seizes the small bird kill from the tiercel. #5 2:09:32 P.M. - the small bird is in the beak of fledgling #1. #6 2:09:33 P.M. - fledgling #1 turns away from the tiercel as fledgling #2 approaches. #7 2:09:33 P.M. - fledgling #1 turns away from fledgling #2. #8 2:09:33 P.M. - fledgling #2 pokes its head under the wing of fledgling #1. #9 2:09:34 P.M. - fledgling steps further away. #10 2:09:34 P.M. - the tercel lifts off the south perch ledge four seconds after arriving with food. #11 2:09:35 P.M. - fledgling #1 has its back to fledgling #2. #12 2:09:36 P.M. - fledgling #1 continues to hold the prey item. #13 2:10:31 P.M. - fledgling #1 moves to the far side of the south perch ledge. #14 2:10:33 P.M. - close up of fledgling #1 with prey item. #15 2:10:34 P.M. - the small prey item has been moved to the talons of fledgling #1. #16 2:10:39 P.M. - the two fledglings, one with prey. #17 2:10:42 P.M. - fledgling #1 looks at fledgling #2, defiantly. #18 2:11:50 P.M. - profile of fledgling #2.

Media notes: falcon flushed a huge flock of gulls and managed to get a slow Heerman’s Gull
Observation Details: Peregrine flushed a huge flock of gulls and managed to catch one slow Heermann’s Gull; Keith Gress got me some info on this bird’s age and sex from expert at GGRO. Based on molt, he aged her at 2-3 years old. The brown feathers are adult feathers. In the female they have juvenile plumage, then the brown, then the gray. “The buffy and unbarred breast is more typical of continental birds, but with all of the cross-polination on this species, it’s possible we have that here now too.”

***Absolutely wild!! I came down to clubhouse drive to scope the river, and just as I got into looking for ducks, I heard a primeval noise unlike anything I’ve really ever heard. I looked up to see a pair of ravens sitting on the famed OSFL branch and a very pissed off adult female PEFA soaring right next to them. Suddenly this bird dove at both the ravens, putting them up and then viciously going after them. The ravens and the PEFA were both vocalizing, and I realized that the combo of the hoarse Raven calls and some guttural PEFA calls were that odd noise I had initially heard. But the real show came when the PEFA decided to rip around the Landing, weaving in between houses and trees and staying quite low. I’ve gotten to experience many awesome moments with PEFAs, but this quickly topped them all because I can’t remember the last time I had one come flying at me eye-to-eye! Eventually, after various iteration of what I explained here happened a few more times, the ravens got tired and fled, and the PEFA claimed it’s perch on the OSFL branch. It remained undisturbed until a Bald Eagle tried to land on the branch, which led to the PEFA attacking and successfully chasing off the Eagle. Not a very birdy day but this compensated for it all! **Note: this bird was banded but I don’t think I got a read on the numbers

Observation Details: As soon as I reached, I saw the female P1 already feeding on a kill in Block#1perch facing east. Not sure if that was yesterday's cache or freshly caught sometime ago. She fed for about 5 mins and tiercel P2 was not in sight. P1 took off after a brief feeding, went around the Block#1 and came back in a minute now overshot reaching the Block#2 NE perch. Not sure if P2 was perched on the southern face of Block#1, but he followed her and directly landed in to Block#1 East facing perch as if he knows there is something left in the kill.   P2 fed very briefly, within 2 mins took off from there and landed in the box below where P1 was perched. P2 vocalized a bit when he landed and both of them kept looking at each other for some time. P1 slept for a few mins as the closed yellow eyelids were clearly visible, but woke up after a Squirrel ran in the parapet wall of the terrace. At around 6:50, P2 took off making a quick flight around Block#2 and came back flying almost touching P1 with a lot of vocalization. P1 dodged a little but didn't bother any much as P2 continued to make a short soaring and landed in the same face on the western end perch.   A Three-striped Palm Squirrel had now climbed down from the terrace parapet into the window sun-shade where P1 had her kill in Block#1 and started feeding, possibly on the remains of the pigeon kill. It was quite surprising to see the rodent relying of the Peregrines to add some protein to its diet.   At around 7:05,P1 did a short wing stretch and pooped once. These are daily indications that she will take off sooner, that she did in less than an minute and took a short glide followed by quick flight towards west face of Block#2. As expected, within a minute P2 also took to wing and followed the same path of P1. A few feet walk revealed that both of them were perched next to each other on the west face of Block#2 at SW end perch.

Observation Details: Migratory Tundra type of subspecies calidus/japonicus. Adult. We note that it is difficult to separate migratory Peregrines in Australia to subspecies and that eBird does not recognise japonicus as a separate taxon. A dark peregrine with white cheek patch and broad moustachial stripe. It is interesting to note that the shape of the moustachial stripe can vary depending on angle and if the bird is flying vs perched for example: https://ebird.org/checklist/S50611590  This is not the same individual as that seen and photographed at Buffalo Creek on 23 Dec 2022 (https://ebird.org/checklist/S124455395) and 28 Dec 2022 (https://ebird.org/checklist/S124954753). Photos indicate that bird was a juvenile.

As I looked around the inlet I spotted this Juvenile Peregrine Falcon feeding on something. I tried to figure out what it was by taking photos and looking for the remnants of the meal but couldn't tell exactly. It was a peep species but I don't know which one. I kept a good distance away so it would be undisturbed while eating. I never approached it directly and wanted to make it feel comfortable with me being there. After it was done it flew to different spots and twice landed within 50 feet of where I was standing. I was not seen as a threat. Part of that is likely this juveniles innocence to the ways of people and part of that was the respect I showed it. I thought how great it would be if all wildlife could be comfortable around people. I spent probably 20-30 minutes just getting lost in the moment. I felt like it was just me and the falcon on the beach. Maybe it felt the same.

First seen in distance coming up off of beach, there were many irritated gulls in the area. It flew over to the cliffs near me carrying dunlin prey. I noticed the dunlin fighting to escape some time after being brought back to the cliffs so I assume it was caught alive in flight by the peregrine. After becoming settled the peregrine killed the dunlin with several bites to the cranium. After the dunlin stopped fighting the peregrine plucked and ate it.

The peregrine falcon was on the field adjacent to the pond. The falcon had just caught a duck, which I suspect was a wigeon. The falcon was feasting in the area on the field where the wigeons like to graze. When the falcon saw me it flew to a nearby tree and then returned to feeding as I was leaving. The falcon has a band on its right leg, There was a second peregrine falcon nearby, possibly the same pair that Toby Bradshaw reported seeing earlier this year.

Hatch year 2019 unbanded female Peregrine Falcon, observed in flight, then perched on a short log near the shoreline, then relocating further inland on the bar. A small puncture appears in the photo I've seen. Photographed well by Paul Smith.

Pair perched near one another on building ledge; the larger female was feeding on a prey item and then joined by the male.  This ledge is about 6 stories up on the south side of a building with conspicuous red brick facades located at 136 N. 3rd St., roughly 200 yards north of McDonald's on the opposite side of N. Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd. (NMLKJB).  This perch can be viewed from along NMLKJB about 100 yards north of McDonald's.  This is likely a regularly-used perch for these birds given accumulated debris around the female and a report that prey parts were often found on the ground below.

Facial pattern of broad almost entirely black cheek/helmeted look is more consistent with South American cassini subspecies than migratory tundrius; but Fernando Angulo says the facial pattern looks to him more like the migraotry tundrius, possibly a male (I thought the large size looked more liek a female). Fernando says "It’s the migratory one, tundrius, probably a male. The cassini has very closed “hood”, almost no “moustache” noticeable. Also, tundrius is very white on the breast, cassini creamy." Thanks Fernando for the feedback.

Locality: Ontario, Fort Erie, opposite residence 411 Niagara Boulevard
Observation Details: I drove to Fort Erie to look for the reported Harlequin Duck (no luck) found by Marcie Jacklin last weekend. Heading home I observed an adult Peregrine Falcon feeding on a small duck directly in front of a small group of Canada Geese on the grassy shoreline edge of the Niagara River. The catch must have just happened as I witnessed in the surrounding air a considerable amount of feathers that were just plucked from the bird. As well before long I was amazed to see the Peregrine throw the ducks head with it's bill several feet away from it's position on the grass. I remained in the car using it as a blind and photographed the action. The Peregrine paid no attention to me and the 18 Canada Geese that were no more than 20 feet away continued to feed and were totally oblivious of the Peregrines presence.   A passing motorist exited his car to observe the bird and flushed it. The only part of the ducks body that remained on the grass was the head.  The deceased duck was an adult female Bufflehead....note the ducks eye remains open!!

One of the falcons was visibly larger when seen in flight.  This bird flew directly over me, paralyzing me from even reaching for my camera...such amazing flight, I couldn't look away. Without a doubt, one of my top 5 favorite birds.

Media notes: Adult male, Gigi, coming in for a landing on the tower.
Observation Details: A lot of activity atop the news tower this morning with both adults flying around the tower numerous times and the adult female seemingly trying to show the young male chick how to fly off the tower.  At 9:50 am Hightower, the young male flew off the tower and around the building where he lost lift and came down in the parking lot where he was rescued successfully.  They took him back up to released him back in the nest area where he promptly flew off again this time north and then west across the Rock River where he landed atop another building and stayed there for most of the afternoon.  Pictures taken.

Observation Details: Both adults enjoying afternoon sun on the double cross bar utility pole south side parking area; in female photo below, a nice look at the nostril cone; falcons have a cone (baffle) just inside each nostril that disrupts the air flow and reduces the pressure of the air entering the respiratory system...also a nice look at the tomial tooth (click on image to enlarge), known as the “killing tooth.” It is a notch on the cutting edge of the upper beak that is used to sever the prey’s spinal column.

Found the original one that was very vocal with the only description that comes to mind was that it sounds like short yips or yipping or short shrieking barks. When this one came down lower and went to perch. I had to find it! And when I did. There was a second Peregrine Falcon. I slowly walked with camera in hand long ways next to my leg and didn't' look directly at them. short peripherals to make sure they were still there. I sat down and started taking photos of the best looking one with the better setting for a photo. Twenty minutes had gone by and both started yipping and looking up. Managed to catch two more streaming and right into direction of the sun. Then a third straggler streamed above. My 2 blandair birds were getting ready to take off. And when they did they elevated very rapidly and had caught the same stream and were gone. The Peregrine Falcon is my all time favorite bird!

Observation Details: continuing bird.  falcon flew high over Congress Ave. and then vaulted up to perch on a ledge near the eastern face of the 26th floor at The Austonian, (Congress @ 2nd) downtown Austin.  this is another favored late afternoon shaded spot for this individual, and is directly across from the JW Marriott.  immediately recognized as being the large blue-gray/rusty falcon seen this morning at the JW Marriott.  large stocky falcon, rusty/pale below, dark blue-gray above, long pointed wings, yellow eye ring, cere, and feet seen.  dark helmet head look.  unmistakable flight style-bold, fast, but muscling swiftly through the air with rapid wing beats.  no translucent areas to under wing as in Kestrel or Red-shouldered Hawk.  great nesting box site and bat hunting post.  this predator has been holding territory here off and on for over two years.

At one point, just about every shorebird to the west of us took flight all at once and scattered into several flocks, which immediately suggested the presence of a Peregrine. Sure enough, one was swooping in from the west at a high speed; it flew into (or maybe through?) one of the roiling flocks of peeps and continued east parallel to the beach, not more than a meter or two above the water. It then headed up and continued to the east, quickly disappearing from sight. The whole thing unfolded in a matter or seconds, but was awesome to see.  As far as we could tell (and something later confirmed by looking at a few photos), it left the beach  empty-handed. Or empty-taloned, as it were.

I was driving home on a residential street in Eastport, Maine when I saw a small, young peregrine tearing apart a presumed pigeon on the sidewalk.  I stopped and took a few photos before a passing car flushed the bird.  I assume that it is of the tundrius subspecies because of its thin moustachial stripe, and a male by its small and slight size.  I've seen peregrines annually in Eastport and this was the smallest one that I remember.  There are a few gray feathers coming in on the scaps and the flank that suggest this was last year's chick.

As I walked past the Apple Juice Plant on Collins Rd I heard a loud hoarse "kak kak kak", I turned to the direction of the sound to see a crow flying over this Peregrine Falcon on the top of a utility pole. I watched as it ate the blue jay. And decided to move on so as not to disturb its meal. As I turned onto Kars Street I again heard the "kak kak kak" and looked up to see the Pergrine being harassed by another Peregrine, the first bird clutching its meal in its talons. I would have missed the whole show if the crow had not been brave enough to fly close to the falcon!

The bird apparently flew on board in the port of Long Beach and roosted on back of ship's funnel.  It was discovered by the ship naturalist.  Every morning, the naturalist would collect any seabirds which had landed on the ship during the night.  She would examine the birds to assure they were not injured, and keep them until they could be released the next morning.  On the morning of the 16th, she released a petrel, only to watch as a bird swooped in and caught it.  A search turned up this falcon.  The falcon stayed with the ship until we docked in Honolulu, where it flew off.

Chick was not on the nest ledge when we arrived at 12:15pm, adult female was in the gum tree. About 15mins later calls heard lower down and then we observed the chick in the water directly below the nest very close to the wall. It struggled against the weed and moved to the left about 20mts. Then clambered up a rock ledge about half a metre above the water. It was still in the same spot an hour later. UPDATE: We were informed later by another observer that during the following hour after we left both adults flew to the rock face above the chick and encouraged it to climb to a higher ledge.

The Peregrine was eating a  Pigeon that the Peregrine had just caught. First the Peregrine snaps the neck. The Peregrine was sort of mantling its food. We were watching it eat the Pigeon from behind tinted windows, so I don’t believe the Peregrine could see us watching it eat. I am posting this sighting about 4 years after making the initial observation, and taking the photos. Some of the photos show a leg band on the Peregrine. We got enough photos of the bird on the ledge as well as visuals, to be able to piece together the numbers on the the tag,  and look up the Peregrine in a database, As I recall, I think this was a female bird who was born on or near the lock and dam in  Minneapolis. I can’t remember exactly how old we calculated the bird to be at the time, but I want to say it was about two and a half years old at the time. All to this is based on my memory of the events 4 years later,  because I did not write down the info about the tag contemporaneously to making the observation. But it was quite memorable and stuck in my mind.On a separate occassion, we saw the Peregrine catch a Pigeon out of midair right in front of our eyes, 15 stories up. (This particular room of our office had a great big bank of windows, 20 feet by 20 feet.) The Peregrine hit the pigeon like a baseball bat, out of nowhere, as the Pigeon was just flying along.

First observed diving at American Wigeon at around 10:20. It perched for about 30 minutes in a tree hanging over the west side of the lake near the AmWi. It flew toward the dam and perched for a brief time on a log at the lake shore and then repositioned to a tree near the entrance building and pier near the dam. Flew over the dam and scattered the ring billed gulls before swooping back up the lake. After I lost sight of it, Joe reported it ate the American Wigeon about 10 minutes later. Checkerboard breast (some breast feathers tawny) and underside of wings, strong mustache stripe, pale eyebrow, brown streak along crown, tawny throat, dark blue back, yellow legs, primaries did not extend beyond tail. Banded on May 21st 2021 in New Jersey with Band Number 1947-31935 BM71 Black over Green by the State of New Jersey - Nongame, Kathleen Clark. The Peregrine Falcon was too young to fly when banded on 21 May 2021. Since Peregrine Falcons fledge around 40 days, this individual must be about 7-8 months old.

Two birds (likely pair), jointly attacking the breeding colonies of Avocets and Stilts on Marsh main islet. Just before the falcons attack I counted 26 Avocets only on the main islet, during the attack it turned out that there were 42 of them (not including juveniles). Most adult Avocets along with the Stilts created a joint defensive, the end result was that the falcons ended up empty handed (or rather empty taloned). The Falcons then flew off towards Martinez. In recent months, I have reported several sighting of Peregrine Falcon in this area (marshes of southern Suisun Bay), this is the first time I have seen two birds together. I suspect they breeds somewhere in the area, either in Contra Costa or in Solano county.

I was just writing this checklist when I was told about there being a Falcon right outside the front window!! Of course, I quickly but quietly grabbed my camera, set myself up amongst the cushions... and there, brimming with power, darting sharp glances in every directions, was a perfect Peregrine!!! The alertness of this creature absolutely astonished me; even from this great distance, and with me behind a window, it immediately locked eyes with me, on edge, daring me to make my move!! I bagged shot after shot before trying to sneak a little closer... and that was it. Immediately, the Peregrine turned and leapt off its branch, and so ended another wonderful time in the presence of a very old favourite!!
Pen B

Media notes: There were three immature birds all calling for the adult bird. The adult was very aggressive towards our presence and made us wait until they left the location before we could continue down the trail.  This was a peak experience for sure!
Observation Details: Five of us are trapped on the trail by a scolding female Peregrine Falcon with at least 3 of the 4 first year birds from the Precipice Trail. I had seen them together diving and playing with each other the day before. These are the recently fledged Precipice birds. This eastern side of MDI has tall Pinus strobus and rock cliffs which are perfect places to hunt for food and protect the immature birds. It is because of the rugged outcroppings along this eastern coast of MDI that our Peregrine 's are doing so well. As we tried to walk down the trail to the van the adult female came toward us very aggressively and trapped us momentarily on the trail with an aggressive behavior I have not seen before for this species. Her aggressive approach and loud scolding was more Goshawk-like. When the adult started calling all 3 immature birds flew into a large White Pine which we passed by earlier and then initially found the birds. The trail is really the only way back to our van so we were stuck. At one point the adult bird flew close enough that we were forced to take cover behind a partial blow-down.  We waited in amazementbehind that tree for about 15 minutes when the female abruptly departed, I suspect, having assessed that we were not a threat. The photo of the immature Peregrine was taken during our first close encounter when we first arrived

Immature Peregrine  with one dark colored band on left leg that I was unable to get a clear picture of, and a second band on the right leg that appeared to be covered up by yellow tape.   After sharing these photos with the Chicago Peregrin Program, a post was made on their Facebook page with these pictures asking people for help with possibly identifying this Peregrine.  Based on the portion of the black tag that could be read,  The Canadian peregrine foundation believes that if the tag reads "S/56" then this is a female fledgling named "Louise" from a downtown Toronto Canada nest from the past spring/summer.  If anybody else happens to spot this bird out in the DeKalb County area or anywhere else and can get a clearer picture of the black band on it's left leg,  message that picture with the location to the Chicago Peregrine foundation Facebook page.

Found by 4-5 Blue-faced Honeyeaters 07.48 which hung around it for a few minutes. 08.12 Rainbow Lorikeets come for a look and Peregrine makes a lunge for one with talons and takes off tho not really pursuing lorikeets. Lands back on different perch on water tower. Remained here when I left .

Observation Details: Juvenile. At ~5:45AM, a juvenile Peregrine circled over, seemingly scouting the protected beach .. a few minutes later, the Peregrine reappeared diving down at Imani and the chicks on the protected beach. Imani took flight and led the Peregrine out over the lake, over the course of the next few minutes the aerial pursuit was on and on a few occasions the Peregrine very nearly nabbing Imani. During the pursuit, a Purple Martin started dive-bombing the Peregrine and a Least Sandpiper flying by also caught the attention of the Peregrine, it was with these distractions that Imani was able to get away. JFC.

Locality: Seacoast Drive to Tijuana River mouth
Observation Details: A juv. It came onto the scene trying to take a fledgeling Gull-billed turn from the ground. It was immediately mobbed by the adult terns while the fledgelings scattered screaming. Then the Least Tern adults started in on it and did not let up. It went down to the edge of the surf, and even into it when a wave ran higher up the beach, and tried to drink the salt water. It went up and down the beach mostly at the edge of the surf as the Least Terns repeatedly swooped down on it.

Cuando llego Urraca está en la antena y Brisa dando vueltas al edificio reclamando y portando una paloma. Al momento se posa con la presa en la azotea, y la joven baja a recogerla. Brisa se va pero vuelve al instante y se posa junto a la caja. 10:57. Madrigal aparece volando desde el sureste, zona puente de los Tres Árboles, remontando mientras reclama. Tras un minuto aproximadamente, se va por donde ha venido. 11:01. Urraca vuelve a la antena. 11:09. Baja a donde está su madre y hacen intercambio de posadero. 11:12. Llega Madrigal y se posa no visible. 12:03. Llega Viento y se posa en una viga. 12:13. Brisa vuela dirección este. 12:29. Viento reclama amenazante ante el paso de una calzada (f.c.) pero no se mueve de su posadero. 12:51. Pasa una calzada (f.o.) a una distancia aproximada a la de la anterior y Viento no se inmuta. 12:55. Viento reclama de alerta pero no consigo ver la amenaza. 13:02. Urraca se asoma a la cornisa, junto a su padre. Reclaman ambos. 13:07. Urraca y Madrigal vuelan varios minutos alrededor del edificio, jugando entre ellas. 13:12. Se posan en zona no visible. 13:16. Un milano negro baja a la azotea, seguramente a por restos de presas. Viento arremete con furia sobre él y lo expulsa. Una de las jóvenes también azuza al milano pero manteniendo la distancia. Viento realiza picados terribles sobre la rapaz que no tarda en huir. Cuando me voy están las dos jóvenes en la azotea. Una en la antena y la otra no visible. ¡No ha pasado ni una paloma bravía en toda la mañana!

Primer día que consigo observar a los dos adultos posados junto a la caja, desde el día de las cópulas, lo que me permite mejorar las fotos del macho. Chillan los dos a un milano negro que vuela bajo. El macho se ausenta por unos 10'. A las 13:49, con buena luz, puedo hacer mejores fotos del macho nuevamente posado, comprobando que porta anilla de lectura... Vuelve a volar enseguida. El macho pica sobre una paloma torcaz a las 14:17, sin éxito. A las 14:22 vuelan juntos remontando sobre el edificio. Brisa persigue en horizontal a dos palomas bravías, sin éxito, en dos ocasiones. 14:36: Brisa llega reclamando, con una paloma bravía recién muerta y entra directa al nido.

Locality: Southern Glades Trail (C111 Canal outside ENP)

Observation Details: Seen at 9:20 when the 100+ ducks, 50+ coots, assorted shorebirds & gulls sounded a terrible clamorous alarm. The ducks & coots went into the water, the coots into a huddle and the ducks into a long line several ducks deep. After scanning the sky in vain, I saw a Peregrine Falcon sitting a few yards further up the beach, eating a coot. Gradually the ducks & coots started to go back to shore, then at 9:30 a runner went past the falcon, which flushed and circled over the water. The alarm resumed, and the falcon landed in a nearby palm tree. Eventually I walked on, leaving the falcon in the tree. About 10 minutes later I looked back and saw the falcon had returned to eating the coot on the beach.

Locality: San Juan Creek mouth, Dana Point

Observation Details: It was quite active all over the water body in the sanctuary.. noticed a flock of 4 Ruddy Shelducks flying low and fast, jinking frequently… realised there was a chase on .. then it tangled with a Marsh Harrier in the palms… saw it a bit later making some low dives .. after an hour it was out again.. harassing Ibises.. they were screaming away and some close aerial calls they settled in the  trees next to the waterbody.. the harassment continued though .. then it bullied some kites .. and was chased by 3 of them in turn .. all between 9:45-11:30 am  or so .. it was identified as a dark morph of a Red-naped Shaheen/ Red-capped Peregrine
